    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-04-16T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-04-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="17"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.00/1541</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gonzales</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-04-16">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 16, 1919</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received April 22.</hi>]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 989</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Department’s instruction No. 775
                    of March 24,<note n="11" xml:id="d17fn11">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_10">p. 10</ref>.</note> and to
                    my despatch No. 985, of April 15, in reply thereto, I have the honor to report
                    that in President Menocal’s semi-annual message to the Congress, published some
                    days ago, I find the following reference to the official work of General
                    Crowder: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“I intend to address in due course a special message to Congress
                            containing the report which I have requested of the illustrious <pb
                                facs="0102" n="17" xml:id="pg_17"/> ex-President of the Advisory
                            Commission of 1906, who in large part drafted the electoral law now in
                            force, Major General E. H. Crowder, U.S. Army, and who by authorization
                            of his Government and at my invitation, is at present in this capital
                            engaged in this important task, and I am sure that his exceptional
                            ability in this line of work will be very helpful for the
                            recommendations which I shall at the proper time submit to the
                            consideration and resolution of Congress.[”]</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">William E. Gonzales</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
